Keymap and notes for using a Mac keyboard on AmigaOne/OS4.  Please note that the following files and information must be used at your own risk, and by using them you are agreeing that I am not responsible for any loss of data, hardware malfunction etc caused by them.

Comments can be emailed to Chris Young <chris@unsatisfactorysoftware.co.uk>
http://www.unsatisfactorysoftware.co.uk
@endnode

@node keymap "Installing gb_mac_ISO-8859-15"
Use the supplied installation script.  This will also download and install AllKeys if requested, and if http-handler is available.

Or manually:
Copy the file gb_mac_ISO-8859-15 to DEVS:Keymaps.
Launch SYS:Prefs/Input and select the keymap marked as "British Mac".  Test it in the provided gadget before saving.

Optionally, copy allkeys.prefs to ENVARC: and install AllKeys from Aminet/OS4Depot.

This keymap was designed for model number M9034B/A and other models may differ.
@endnode

@node notes "Keymap Notes"
A lot of the keycaps on the Mac keyboard are different from those on British PC keyboards, so I've had to move some popular characters.  Other than that printed on the keycaps, the significant changes are:
Superscript 1,2,3 are on Shift-Alt 1,2,3 (this is to accomodate Euro on Alt-2)
# is on both Alt-3 and Alt-\\
Everything else works as marked on the keys.  The Apple/Command keys act as Amiga keys.

The Help key acts as an Insert key.  If you want it to act as Help, you need to download AllKeys from http://www.os4depot.net and copy the supplied allkeys.prefs to ENVARC:.  This also enables the volume keys to control Mixer (if running) and Eject (command will need to be edited for this).

Some of the keys are not available, even with AllKeys.  They are:
F13, F14, F15, F16, Clear* and NumPad =

* Clear seems to work internally as a NumLock key, and not pass any RawKey code to the OS.
@endnode

@node usbkbd "USB Keyboards in U-Boot"
To use a USB keyboard within U-Boot, you need to type the following commands (the first command will need to be typed from a PS/2 keyboard connected to the Amiga, and if it fails, the second command won't be typeable):

setenv stdin usbkbd
saveenv

Note that a few key combinations don't seem to work in U-Boot.  Most notably, Ctrl-C and the left/right cursor keys.

To switch back to a PS/2 keyboard, you will need to type (from the USB keyboard initially):

setenv stdin ps2kbd
saveenv
@endnode

@node unotes "USB Keyboard/Mouse Notes"
You can run your Amiga without a PS/2 keyboard attached if you have followed all the steps on the previous pages.  However, there are a few pitfalls:

1. USB Keyboard and Mouse
With both a USB keyboard and mouse, it is currently impossible to enter the Early Startup Menu (usually accessed by holding down both mouse buttons or the Help key on boot).  When USB becomes part of Kickstart this will no longer be an issue.

2. Unavailable keys
There are certain keys that aren't available on the Apple keyboard that are on standard PC keyboards.  These are: Insert*, NumLock*, Print Screen/SysReq, Scroll Lock, Pause/Break.

There are also keys on the keyboard which are not currently useable, even with AllKeys.*

* See @{"notes" link notes} for more information.

3. With no PS/2 keyboard attached, a few seconds are added to the U-Boot process as it tries to detect a PS/2 keyboard.  I cannot currently find a way to stop this, other than leaving a PS/2 keyboard attached.

4. From my experience, with the keyboard and a USB mouse attached directly to the Amiga, attaching another device causes OS4 to complain about over-current and shut the hub down, in fact I even had problems with the keyboard and mouse being shut down or not detected when there were no other devices attached.  It is best to connect the keyboard to a self-powered USB hub.

5. Note that the the earlier revisions of the AmigaOne XE have a problem with detecting when USB devices are plugged or unplugged.  There is a hardware fix for the XE problem, but it can also be solved by using a USB hub.  This keyboard contains a hub and two USB ports, but see point 4 above.
@endnode

